### Headquarters

One part of [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) headquarters in [Woodlawn, Maryland](/Woodlawn,_Maryland)
Another view of [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) headquarters in Maryland

The [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) holds the rather distinctive honor of being among the first federal agencies to strategically place its national headquarters outside the immediate gravitational pull of [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.), or its adjacent, ever-expanding suburbs. This seemingly unusual decision was born out of a pragmatic, if somewhat mundane, necessity: the sheer volume of paper records required. Back in 1936, a suitable edifice capable of housing an unprecedented quantity of documents simply wasn't available within the nation's capital. Consequently, the [Social Security Board](/Social_Security_Board) opted for the [Candler Building](/Candler_Building) on [Baltimore's](/Baltimore,_Maryland) historic [Inner Harbor](/Inner_Harbor) as a temporary, albeit substantial, solution.

No sooner had the agency settled in than plans were set in motion for a permanent, purpose-built headquarters in [Washington](/Washington,_D.C.), specifically designed to accommodate their prodigious record storage requirements. However, fate, or perhaps just exceptionally bad timing, intervened. By the time this grand new building reached completion, the world had plunged into [World War II](/World_War_II), and the nascent structure was swiftly commandeered by the [War Department](/United_States_Department_of_War) for more pressing national defense needs. After the war's conclusion, the logistical nightmare of relocating the entire agency from [Baltimore](/Baltimore,_Maryland) to [Washington](/Washington,_D.C.) was deemed too disruptive, a decision that likely saved countless headaches and moving expenses. Thus, the agency remained comfortably, or perhaps resignedly, ensconced in the [Candler Building](/Candler_Building) until 1960, when it finally moved into its newly constructed, sprawling headquarters in [Woodlawn](/Woodlawn,_Maryland).

The thoroughfare that gracefully leads to this federal behemoth, a road specifically engineered for the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration)'s convenience, bears the fitting name [Security Boulevard (Maryland Route 122)](/Maryland_Route_122). This artery has since blossomed into one of the major conduits connecting [Baltimore](/Baltimore,_Maryland) with its western suburbs, a testament to the agency's enduring presence. The very exit from the nearby [Baltimore Beltway (Interstate 695)](/Interstate_695_(Maryland)) that serves the headquarters is also named Security Boulevard. The nomenclature has even permeated the local commercial landscape, with a nearby [shopping center](/Shopping_center) christened [Security Square Mall](/Security_Square_Mall), leading to the informal, if slightly uninspired, local appellation of [Woodlawn](/Woodlawn,_Maryland) as "Security." Adding another layer of bureaucratic permanence, [Interstate 70](/Interstate_70), a highway that spans thousands of miles from the deserts of [Utah](/Utah) to the tidewater of [Maryland](/Maryland), rather unceremoniously terminates in a [park and ride](/Park_and_ride) lot that conveniently adjoins the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) campus.

Due to the inevitable constraints of physical space and the perpetual cycle of renovations that afflict any large institution, a significant portion of headquarters employees now operate from leased office spaces scattered throughout the [Woodlawn](/Woodlawn,_Maryland) area. Furthermore, not all [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) components are co-located with the main headquarters. For instance, the central office of [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration)'s Office of Disability Adjudication and Review, a body with a rather verbose name and an even more verbose manual, is situated in [Falls Church, Virginia](/Falls_Church,_Virginia), proving that even within a single agency, geography can be a fickle mistress.

### Field offices

The [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) maintains an extensive, indispensable network of over 1,200 community-based [field offices](/Social_Security_Administration#Field_offices) across the [United States](/United_States). These offices serve as the primary direct point of contact for the public, acting as the front lines of the agency's operations. In fiscal year 2019, a remarkable 43 million individuals darkened the doors of these [field offices](/Social_Security_Administration#Field_offices), seeking assistance for a myriad of reasons: applying for benefits, obtaining an original or replacement [Social Security card](/Social_Security_card), or simply navigating the labyrinthine complexities of their entitlements. It's a volume of human interaction that would make a less resilient institution simply give up.

As previously noted, these critical public-facing offices were compelled to close their physical doors for a two-year period due to the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic), a disruption that undoubtedly caused widespread inconvenience and a backlog of services. They finally, and perhaps reluctantly, resumed in-person services in April 2022, allowing citizens to once again engage directly with the agency.

For those attempting to locate one of these elusive offices, the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) provides a convenient [field office locator service](/Social_Security_Administration#Field_offices) on its website, offering access to phone numbers and addresses – a small concession to user-friendliness.

Beyond the brick-and-mortar locations, the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) extends its reach through a national toll-free number (1-800-772-1213) and a comprehensive website. The digital portal allows for the online application of [retirement](/Retirement) and [disability](/Disability) benefits, streamlining a process that once demanded physical presence. However, for the more delicate matter of survivor benefits, individuals are still required to either call or visit an [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) office in person to initiate their application – a nod, perhaps, to the inherent complexities and sensitivities of such claims. In a move towards greater digital convenience, most states now permit individuals to apply for a [replacement Social Security card](/Social_Security_card) online, saving untold hours of waiting in line.

Furthermore, the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration)'s [field offices](/Social_Security_Administration#Field_offices) are also the designated points of contact for applying for [Supplemental Security Income](/Supplemental_Security_Income) (SSI). The diligent staff within these offices often go a step further, assisting eligible [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) applicants with the application process for food assistance through the [Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP)](/Supplemental_Nutrition_Assistance_Program), thereby providing a more holistic approach to aiding those in need.

### Program Service Centers

The true engine room of the [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration)'s benefit processing operations lies within its six expansive [Program Service Centers](/Social_Security_Administration#Program_Service_Centers), strategically positioned across the country. These facilities are where the bulk of the initial benefit claims are meticulously processed and where subsequent adjustments to existing benefits are painstakingly managed. It's a complex, high-volume undertaking, far removed from the public-facing interactions of the [field offices](/Social_Security_Administration#Field_offices).

Historically, the two cornerstone positions within these [Program Service Centers](/Social_Security_Administration#Program_Service_Centers) have been Claims Authorizers and Benefits Authorizers. Claims Authorizers, who are now sometimes referred to by the rather more modern title of claims specialists, bear the crucial responsibility of establishing the initial benefits for program recipients. Their counterparts, Benefits Authorizers, are tasked with the intricate work of processing often complicated changes to entitlements for existing beneficiaries. This includes navigating the labyrinth of life events, such as changes in marital status or income, as well as addressing the equally complex issues of overpayments, underpayments, and other adjustments. The claims position traditionally held a higher rank, initially requiring a college degree, whereas the post-entitlement position did not, a distinction that speaks to the perceived complexity of initial adjudication versus ongoing management. For decades, the processing of these post-entitlement actions has been handled through a system known as [Manual Adjustment, Credit and Award Processes (MADCAP)](/Manual_Adjustment,_Credit_and_Award_Processes), a name that subtly hints at the laborious nature of the work.

The six critical [Program Service Centers](/Social_Security_Administration#Program_Service_Centers) are located in:

*   The Northeastern Program Service Center, currently in [Jamaica, Queens, New York](/Jamaica,_Queens,_New_York), having moved there in the late 1980s from its prior locations in [Rego Park, Queens](/Rego_Park,_Queens) and [College Point, Queens](/College_Point,_Queens).
*   The Mid-Atlantic Program Service Center, situated in [Philadelphia, Pennsylvania](/Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania).
*   The Southeastern Program Service Center, found in [Birmingham, Alabama](/Birmingham,_Alabama).
*   The Great Lakes Program Service Center, operating out of [Chicago, Illinois](/Chicago,_Illinois).
*   The Mid-America Program Service Center, located in [Kansas City, Missouri](/Kansas_City,_Missouri).
*   The Western Program Service Center, which has been in [Richmond, California](/Richmond,_California) since the mid-1970s, having previously operated from [San Francisco](/San_Francisco).

These six cities have continuously housed these vital service centers since at least the early 1950s, a testament to their strategic importance. The origins of these payment centers can be traced back to 1942, when they were initially designated as Area Offices. The very first was established in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania), swiftly followed by others in [New York](/New_York), [Chicago](/Chicago,_Illinois), [San Francisco](/San_Francisco), and [New Orleans, Louisiana](/New_Orleans,_Louisiana).

In addition to these primary centers, specialized processing units exist for specific functions, such as the Office of Earnings and International Operations and the Office of Disability Operations, both conveniently located in [Baltimore](/Baltimore,_Maryland), near the agency's headquarters.

Before the mid-1970s, these facilities were simply known as Payment Centers. However, by the late 1960s, these Payment Centers had unfortunately garnered a reputation for rather dismal bureaucratic performance, becoming places where few desired to work. In a commendable effort to rectify this, a significant reorganization under a "modules system" was undertaken during the 1970s. This innovative system aimed to improve efficiency and morale by assigning each module a specific block of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) numbers, thereby empowering each unit to comprehensively process all aspects of a claim, from initial entitlement through various changes, notifications to beneficiaries, and so forth. Decades later, this modules system was still widely regarded as one of the most substantial and successful improvements in [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) processing history.

The sheer scale of these centers means each has typically employed around two thousand people or more, bestowing upon them a significant local economic impact. Consequently, even proposed relocations *within* the same metropolitan area have frequently ignited considerable political conflict. For example, in the early 1970s, when the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) and the [General Services Administration](/General_Services_Administration) announced their intention to shift payment center operations from [San Francisco](/San_Francisco) across the [East Bay](/East_Bay_(San_Francisco_Bay_Area)) to [Richmond](/Richmond,_California), the move was vehemently opposed by [San Francisco](/San_Francisco)-representing Congressman [Phillip Burton](/Phillip_Burton). Despite Burton's earnest efforts, construction proceeded in a [Richmond](/Richmond,_California) redevelopment area, and the relocation was completed around 1975.

A similar, equally contentious saga unfolded in the late 1970s when the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration), the [General Services Administration](/General_Services_Administration), and the [Carter administration](/Carter_administration) conceived a plan to move the program service center from its primary location – two leased buildings on [Horace Harding Expressway](/Horace_Harding_Expressway) in [Lefrak City](/Lefrak_City), [Rego Park](/Rego_Park,_Queens) – to a gleaming new federal building slated for a revitalization zone in the heart of the [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens,_New_York) area of [Queens](/Queens). This move was enthusiastically championed by Congressman [Joseph P. Addabbo](/Joseph_P._Addabbo), who represented [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens,_New_York) and whose district stood to gain over 2,000 federal workers. Conversely, it faced fierce opposition from Congressman [Benjamin Rosenthal](/Benjamin_Stanley_Rosenthal), whose district would suffer the loss of these jobs. According to Rosenthal, the potential negative repercussions of the move would most severely impact the [Elmhurst](/Elmhurst,_Queens) and [Corona](/Corona,_Queens) neighborhoods. The relocation also garnered support from Representative [Geraldine Ferraro](/Geraldine_Ferraro), another influential figure from [Queens](/Queens) who held a seat on the powerful [House Public Works Committee](/United_States_House_Committee_on_Transportation_and_Infrastructure). The dispute escalated into Congressional hearings, drawing in prominent figures like Senator [Daniel Patrick Moynihan](/Daniel_Patrick_Moynihan), who supported the move, and developer [Richard Lefrak](/Richard_Lefrak), who opposed it. Ultimately, the relocation proceeded, and the new, impressive 11-story building in [Jamaica](/Jamaica,_Queens,_New_York) – by then posthumously named the [Joseph P. Addabbo Federal Building](/Joseph_P._Addabbo_Federal_Building) after the congressman's passing – officially opened its doors in 1988.

### Coverage

The Mid-Atlantic Program Services Center in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia,_Pennsylvania)

Initially, upon its inception, the [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) program, like many nascent government initiatives, was far from universal in its reach. Only a modest 56 percent of the jobs in the [United States](/United_States) were actually encompassed by [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) coverage. Fast forward to today, and the system has achieved a near-universal status, a considerable expansion that now includes approximately 94 percent of individuals engaged in paid employment across the [United States](/United_States) working in covered employment. It's almost as if they eventually figured out how to include most people.

However, "nearly universal" is not "entirely universal," and there remain notable exceptions. State and local government workers, for instance, are not mandated to participate in the [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) program *if* they are already enrolled in a public retirement system provided by their employers. Nevertheless, these state and local governments retain the option to elect participation in the program through specific arrangements known as Section 218 agreements. Of the 23.2 million state and local workers nationwide, a substantial 6.6 million currently remain outside the umbrella of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) coverage. Other categories of workers who typically do not fall under [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) include federal employees hired prior to 1984, [railroad workers](/Railroad_Retirement_Board), certain family employees, some students, and a segment of the clergy.

For those whose employment falls outside the purview of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)), the implications are straightforward: neither the workers nor their employers contribute [Social Security payroll taxes](/Social_Security_tax). Consequently, these individuals are generally ineligible to receive [Social Security retirement](/Retirement) and [disability benefits](/Disability) unless they have accrued sufficient work history in [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) covered employment at other points in their careers. Before 2025, individuals who split their careers between covered and non-covered employment, and who received pensions from their non-covered work, often faced reductions in their [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) benefits due to the [Windfall Elimination Provision (WEP)](/Windfall_Elimination_Provision) or the [Government Pension Offset (GPO)](/Social_Security_Government_Pension_Offset). These provisions, which often struck beneficiaries as rather unfair, were finally abolished with the commendable passage of the [Social Security Fairness Act](/Social_Security_Fairness_Act), a legislative change that likely brought a sigh of relief to many.

[Railroad workers](/Railroad_Retirement_Board) have always operated under a distinct system, predating the very establishment of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) itself, administered by the [Railroad Retirement Board](/Railroad_Retirement_Board). They continue to do so today, although a specific portion of each railroad pension is formally designated as "equivalent" to [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) benefits. Furthermore, [railroad workers](/Railroad_Retirement_Board) also participate in [Medicare](/Medicare_(United_States)). It is also worth noting that all state and local government employees hired since 1986, or those covered by Section 218 Agreements, are required to participate in [Medicare](/Medicare_(United_States)), even if their employment is not covered for the purposes of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) benefits. The government, it seems, has a particular fondness for ensuring healthcare coverage.

### Old age, survivors and disability

The [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) is the steward of a trio of crucial social insurance programs: [retirement](/Retirement), survivors, and [disability](/Disability). These programs collectively provide monthly benefits designed to support aged or disabled workers, their spouses and children, and the survivors of insured workers who have passed away. In 2010, this vital safety net extended to over 54 million Americans, who collectively received an astounding approximately $712 billion in [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) benefits. These programs, which are collectively known as [Retirement, Survivors, Disability Insurance (RSDI)](/Retirement,_Survivors,_Disability_Insurance), are primarily funded through the dedicated [Social Security taxes](/Social_Security_tax) paid annually by employers, employees, and the self-insured. These revenues are carefully channeled into a special [trust fund](/Social_Security_trust_fund), a fiscal reservoir designed to ensure the long-term solvency of these critical benefits.

A significant, and often emotionally charged, aspect of the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration)'s operations involves the administration of its [disability](/Disability) program. This is partly managed through its [Office of Hearing Operations (OHO)](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations), an entity equipped with regional offices and hearing offices strategically located across the [United States](/United_States). The [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) is responsible for processing claims that have progressed through the initial (in prototype states) or second unfavorable determination made by the state-based [Disability Determination Services (DDS)](/Disability_Determination_Services). These [DDS](/Disability_Determination_Services) offices are the ones that develop and process claims at the initial and reconsideration levels of review. The [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) oversees the operations of approximately 1,200 [Administrative Law Judges (ALJs)](/Administrative_Law_Judge) who, supported by roughly 6,000 staff employees, are tasked with developing, evaluating, and adjudicating appellate claims. They conduct substantive hearings, gathering testimony and expert evidence, before issuing a hearing decision complete with findings of fact and law pertinent to each individual claim. To ensure consistency and procedural integrity, the [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) publishes a comprehensive procedural manual known as the [Hearings, Appeals, and Litigation Law Manual (HALLEX)](/Hearings,_Appeals,_and_Litigation_Law_Manual). This manual meticulously "defines procedures for carrying out policy and provides guidance for processing and adjudicating claims" for the [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) itself, the Appeals Council (AC), and the Division of Civil Actions (DCA) levels. It also incorporates policy statements resulting from Appeals Council en banc meetings, operating under the authority of the Appeals Council Chair.

The [RSDI](/Retirement,_Survivors,_Disability_Insurance) program stands as the preeminent benefits program administered by the [U.S. federal government](/Federal_government_of_the_United_States). For a significant portion of its beneficiaries, these funds represent not just assistance, but a vital, often sole, source of income. Recognizing this profound impact, increasing access to this essential benefit program for low-income or homeless individuals remains a core objective for the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration). The agency is an active member of the [United States Interagency Council on Homelessness](/United_States_Interagency_Council_on_Homelessness), collaborating with various municipal, county, state, local, and federal partners in a concerted effort to enhance access and approval rates for eligible [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income)/[SSDI](/Social_Security_Disability_Insurance) benefits among these vulnerable populations. It's a reminder that beneath the layers of bureaucracy, there are real lives at stake.

### Supplemental Security Income (SSI)

An [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) [field office](/Social_Security_Administration#Field_offices) in [Ann Arbor, Michigan](/Ann_Arbor,_Michigan)

In addition to the contribution-based programs, the [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) also shoulders the responsibility of administering the [Supplemental Security Income (SSI)](/Supplemental_Security_Income) program. This program operates on a fundamentally different premise: it is needs-based, providing crucial financial assistance for the aged, the blind, or the disabled who demonstrate limited income and resources. Before the transformative 1972 Amendments to the [Social Security Act](/Social_Security_Act), low-income aged, blind, or disabled individuals relied on a patchwork of state-run programs, quaintly named [Old-Age Assistance](/Old-Age_Assistance), [Aid to the Blind](/Aid_to_the_Blind), and [Aid to the Permanently and Totally Disabled](/Aid_to_the_Permanently_and_Totally_Disabled). While these programs did receive federal funding, their eligibility requirements and benefit payments varied wildly from state to state, creating an uneven and often inequitable system. The 1972 Amendments swept away this fragmented approach, replacing it with the standardized, federal [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) program. The [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) was duly assigned the task of managing this new program, commencing operations in 1974.

Currently, federal benefit payments under the [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) program can reach up to $943 for an individual and $1,371 for a couple. Unlike the [RSDI](/Retirement,_Survivors,_Disability_Insurance) programs, which are funded by dedicated payroll taxes, [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) benefits are paid directly out of the general revenue of the [United States of America](/United_States). It’s worth noting that some states, in a display of additional generosity or recognition of higher living costs, choose to supplement the federal [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) amount.

Given its needs-based nature, eligibility for [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) is, by design, strictly limited to persons who possess limited income and resources. Furthermore, eligibility is generally restricted to [U.S. citizens](/U.S._citizenship), nationals, and certain other groups (such as some refugees) who maintain residency in one of the 50 [U.S. states](/U.S._states), the [District of Columbia](/District_of_Columbia), or the [Northern Mariana Islands](/Northern_Mariana_Islands). Conversely, [U.S. citizens](/U.S._citizenship) and nationals residing in [American Samoa](/American_Samoa), [Guam](/Guam), [Puerto Rico](/Puerto_Rico), and the [U.S. Virgin Islands](/U.S._Virgin_Islands) are, for reasons that might seem arbitrary to an outsider, not eligible for [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income). In 2019, the program provided a lifeline to 8 million individuals, a figure that included 1.1 million disabled children, 4.6 million disabled adults, and 2.3 million persons aged 65 or older.

In certain scenarios, individuals may find themselves eligible for a rather unique combination of both [Social Security (RSDI)](/Retirement,_Survivors,_Disability_Insurance) benefits and [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) benefits. For example, a disabled individual who previously worked in [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States))-covered employment might receive a [Social Security disability benefit](/Disability) (earned through their prior contributions) concurrently with a partial [SSI](/Supplemental_Security_Income) benefit (due to their current limited income and resources). The [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) refers to these individuals as "concurrent" beneficiaries, a designation that neatly encapsulates their dual eligibility.

### Medicare

While the overarching administration of the vital [Medicare](/Medicare_(United_States)) program is predominantly the responsibility of the [Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services](/Centers_for_Medicare_%26_Medicaid_Services) (CMS), the [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) plays a crucial, albeit supporting, role in several key areas. [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) offices are frequently utilized for determining initial eligibility for [Medicare](/Medicare_(United_States)), facilitating some aspects of premium payments, and serving as points of contact for limited public inquiries. It's a partnership, if a somewhat asymmetrical one.

Furthermore, the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) directly administers a critical financial needs-based program known as "Extra Help." This program is specifically designed to assist [Medicare](/Medicare_(United_States)) beneficiaries in offsetting the costs associated with premiums, deductibles, and coinsurance under [Part D of Medicare](/Medicare_Part_D), which covers prescription drug expenses. The benefits provided through this "Extra Help" program are estimated to be worth approximately $5,000 per year, a significant financial relief for many. Individuals can conveniently apply for the Extra Help program either online or by contacting the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) directly via phone.

### Operations

To ensure a semblance of consistency and, one hopes, efficiency in the treatment of its vast cohort of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) beneficiaries across its sprawling organization, the [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) has meticulously compiled a comprehensive tome known as the [Program Operations Manual System (POMS)](/Program_Operations_Manual_System). This manual, for all its bureaucratic heft, governs practically every conceivable aspect of the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration)'s internal operations. [POMS](/Program_Operations_Manual_System) describes, in excruciating detail, a staggering array of situations regularly encountered by [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) personnel, prescribing the exact policies and procedures that apply to each specific scenario. One can only imagine the sheer volume of paper, or pixels, dedicated to such an endeavor.

### Automation

IBM tabulating machines in use at [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) c.&#8201;1936
A few of the hundreds of keypunch operators [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) employed throughout the late 1930s and into the 1950s

It might surprise some, given the agency's venerable age, that the establishment of [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) actually predated the invention of the modern [digital computer](/Computer). However, this did not mean a lack of automation. Instead, [punched card](/Punched_card) data processing, a remarkably [mature technology](/Mature_technology) for its time, was extensively deployed. From the program's very inception, the [Social Security](/Social_Security_(United_States)) system made widespread and innovative use of automated [unit record equipment](/Unit_record_equipment). This early embrace of technology allowed the [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) to achieve a surprisingly high level of efficiency for an organization of its scale and complexity. Indeed, [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) expenses have historically remained a remarkably small fraction of the total benefits paid out. As a percentage of the assets it manages, the administration costs hover around a mere 0.39%, a figure that would make many a private enterprise blush with envy.

### Adjudication

The [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) operates its own intricate [administrative adjudication system](/Administrative_law), a complex internal judicial structure that possesses [original jurisdiction](/Original_jurisdiction) when claims are denied, either partially or in full. Decisions within this system are rendered by [Administrative Law Judges (ALJs)](/Administrative_Law_Judge) and Senior Attorney Adjudicators, who are supported by a cohort of approximately 6,000 staff employees. These dedicated individuals work at various locations across the [United States](/United_States) under the banner of the [U.S. Office of Hearing Operations (OHO)](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations), an entity formerly known as the Office of Disability Adjudication and Review (ODAR). Their primary role is to hear and decide challenges to [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) decisions, ensuring a layer of administrative review. Should claimants remain dissatisfied with an [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) decision, they retain the right to appeal to the [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations)'s Appeals Council, and if still aggrieved, the final recourse lies with a [U.S. District Court](/United_States_District_Court).

Over the years, the [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) (or ODAR, as it was known) has painstakingly developed its own unique procedural system, a meticulously documented framework outlined in the [Hearings and Appeals Litigation Law Manual (HALLEX)](/Hearings,_Appeals,_and_Litigation_Law_Manual). This comprehensive manual serves as the definitive guide for all adjudicatory processes within the office. Prior to its rebranding as [ODAR](/Office_of_Disability_Adjudication_and_Review) in 2007, to more accurately reflect the fact that roughly 75% of its docket consisted of [disability cases](/Disability), the office was known as the Office of Hearings and Appeals (OHA), and before the 1970s, it bore the even more formal title of the Bureau of Hearings and Appeals. Beyond its primary focus on [disability](/Disability), [OHO](/Office_of_Hearing_Operations) (or ODAR) also adjudicates disputes related to [retirement claims](/Retirement_Insurance_Benefits) and maintains jurisdiction over issues concerning the paternity of a claimant or the validity of a marriage when a claim for benefits is filed under the earnings record of a spouse or parent. The agency also retains a limited number of [Medicare](/Medicare_(United_States)) claim issues, a residual legacy from the era when the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) was still a component of the [U.S. Department of Health and Human Services](/Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services).

### Statistical publications

Each year, in a tradition that precedes the sentimental observance of [Mother's Day](/Mother%27s_Day), the [Social Security Administration](/Social_Security_Administration) releases a highly anticipated list detailing the names most frequently bestowed upon newborn babies in the [United States](/United_States) during the preceding year. This data, a fascinating glimpse into societal naming conventions, is meticulously compiled based on applications for [Social Security cards](/Social_Security_card). The report comprehensively includes the 1,000 most common names for both genders, offering a snapshot of popular culture and enduring trends. The "Popular Baby Names" page on the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) website provides the complete list, along with the added functionality to search for past years and specific names, allowing for endless hours of genealogical or purely curious exploration.

For the sake of individual privacy, a policy that seems increasingly rare these days, the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration) refrains from publishing data for names with fewer than five occurrences in any given year. This is further refined by not publishing data for names with fewer than five occurrences within a single geographic location in any specific year. This cautious approach contrasts with other baby name tracking sources, such as BabyCenter, which do not rely on geographic indicators and can therefore display ranked lists without any name registration minimums. BabyCenter's name reports also offer a distinct advantage by showcasing naming trends in real time, drawing on information from over 500,000 parents who actively register births on their site and app (as of 2024). These emerging trends and annual rankings have been published for more than two decades, often appearing months ahead of the [SSA](/Social_Security_Administration)'s official release. It just goes to show, some things move faster when they're not burdened by the weight of federal bureaucracy.

